{
  "texts": [
    "Related workIn this section, we discuss state-of-the-art deep neural networks for deepfake detection and swarm intelligence algorithms for optimal hyperparameter fine-tuning.",
    "Deepfake detectionOne of the first end-to-end trainable architectures for video classification using CNN and RNN was proposed in 2015 by Liang and Hu [7].",
    "Their work exploited recurrent CNN (RCNN) for undertaking object recognition.",
    "In 2016, Donahue et al. [8] studied Long-Term Recurrent Convolutional Network (LRCN), where a CNN processed raw visual input and fed it to a stack of recurrent sequential models for spatial-temporal feature extraction.",
    "Specifically, the LRCN model adopted CNNs to learn visual features from video frames and passed a sequence of image embeddings through Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks for video classification.In 2018, after the first deepfakes appeared, the idea to use the hybrid architecture for deepfake detection was first researched and published combining the advantageous characteristics of the RNN to enhance the performance of the CNN."
  ]
}